, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Honiton, Devon, England":"Honiton, Devon, England","Cullompton, Devon, England":"Cullompton, Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"en":{"1458–1510":"1458–1510","1465–1515":"1465–1515","1479–1558":"1479–1558","1480–1589":"1480–1589","1485–1525":"1485–1525","1434–1484":"1434–1484","–Female":"Deceased","1525":"1525","1558":"1558","1458":"1458","1479":"1479","1589":"1589","1434":"1434","1510":"1510","1465":"1465","1485":"1485","1484":"1484","1480":"1480","1515":"1515","Cullompton, Devon, , England":"Cullompton, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Melcombe Regis, Dorset, England":"Melcombe Regis, Dorset, England, United Kingdom","Honiton, Devon, England":"Honiton, Devon, England","Cullompton, Devon, England":"Cullompton, Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cockram","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (western): variant of   Cockerham  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cockerham","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): habitational name from a place in Lancashire named Cocker, from the Cocker river (a Celtic name apparently derived from an element <i>kukro</i> ‘winding’) + Old English <i>hām</i> ‘homestead’ or <i>hamm</i> ‘enclosure hemmed in by water’."]}]},{"name":"George","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"George Cockram was born in 1458, in Honiton, Devon, England as the son of James Cockram and EOL Cockeram. He married Lady Edith West in 1479, in Honiton, Devon, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. He died in 1510, in Devon, England, at the age of 52, and was buried in Devon, England."},"et":{"1458–1510":"1458–1510","1465–1515":"1465–1515","1479–1558":"1479–1558","1480–1589":"1480–1589","1485–1525":"1485–1525","1434–1484":"1434–1484","–Female":"Surnud","1525":"1525","1558":"1558","1458":"1458","1479":"1479","1589":"1589","1434":"1434","1510":"1510","1465":"1465","1485":"1485","1484":"1484","1480":"1480","1515":"1515","Cullompton, Devon, , England":"Cullompton, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Melcombe Regis, Dorset, England":"Melcombe Regis, Dorset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Honiton, Devon, England":"Honiton, Devon, England","Cullompton, Devon, England":"Cullompton, Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fi":{"1458–1510":"1458–1510","1465–1515":"1465–1515","1479–1558":"1479–1558","1480–1589":"1480–1589","1485–1525":"1485–1525","1434–1484":"1434–1484","–Female":"Kuollut","1525":"1525","1558":"1558","1458":"1458","1479":"1479","1589":"1589","1434":"1434","1510":"1510","1465":"1465","1485":"1485","1484":"1484","1480":"1480","1515":"1515","Cullompton, Devon, , England":"Cullompton, Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Melcombe Regis, Dorset, England":"Melcomb